column80:
Statistical analyses were performed using JMP Pro V.14.1.0. 
Continuous and categorical variables were reported as median 
(range) and number (percentage), respectively. Differences across 
multiple groups were assessed by the Kruskal-Wallis, Pearson’s 
χ2 or Fisher’s exact test for multiple categories, as appropriate. 
Associations with a poor outcome at last clinical follow-up 
were explored by univariate logistic regression analysis, while 
the simultaneous effect of multiple significant variables was 
assessed by multivariate logistic regression. A two-sided p<0.05 
was considered statistically significant. Adjustment for multiple 
comparisons was not performed.

column7: describe the safety and utility of botulinum toxin in mitigating muscle spasms/rigidity in Stiff Person Syndrome
column70: Our cohort had varied injection sites, including paraspinals 35%, lower extremity 40%, cervical 10%, hand 5%, and abdominal muscles 5%.
column71: Robust response was reported in 30% (6/20), 25% (5/20) reported moderate response, and 40% (8/20) reported poor response amongst which 25% (2/8) had an initial moderate response which abated. Although not consistently recorded, around 25% of our patients were able to decrease their oral medication burden. Among the responders 80% continued with injections. In our study, 55% of patients had a positive response to onabotulinum toxin with subjective improvement in spasms and/or pain along with improvement in quality of life.

column7:
To characterize the distribution, number and frequency
of muscles injected, dosages used, and clinical response to
BoNT in people with SPS.
column75:
Nineteen patients reported improvement in stiffness
and/or spasms after the first injection with effect lasting a
median of 9 weeks. Median patient-reported Likert rating
after the first visit was 4 (IQR 3.5-4.5) and after the third
visit was 5 (IQR 4.5-5). Median change in timed 25-foot
walk between visits 1 and 3 was -0.54 seconds (IQR
-2.87-1.10).
column76:
Common patterns of injected muscles
included cranio-cervical, thoracic/back, hip/pelvis, and distal
lower extremity muscle groups, with median total doses
injected being 257.5 units (IQR 188.8-300.0) at visit 1 and
447.5 units (IQR 292.5-600.0) at visit 3. Muscles were
selected based on patient-specific phenomenological presentation.
Doses up to 795 units were used without adverse
effects.

column7: polysomnography of SPS
column81: Sleep patterns were similar in all patients and were characterised by: long sleep latency; total sleep time reduction; frequent awakenings and EEG arousals; absence of stage 3 and 4 of NREMS; and REM sleep reduction. These findings were not related to leg myoclonus and apnea presence, indicating a disturbance of induction and maintenance of sleep similar to the changes produced by the GABAA receptor dysfunction. No differences in EEG sleep pattern were found with regard to the severity and duration of the disease and between SPS and SLS cases. This suggests an early involvement of both forebrain and GABA also in variants whose spasms and rigidity of limbs mimic a spinal origin.
